[5] USA (Los Angeles County)
Date: Fri 28 Feb 2020
Source: New University [abridged, edited]
https://www.newuniversity.org/2020/02/28/five-people-infected-with-measles-in-la-county/


Five people were infected with measles in Los Angeles County after being in contact with an infected international tourist, according to the Los Angeles County Department of Public Health.

LA Public Health accumulated a list of places that the infected patient visited between 26 Jan and 1 Feb [2020]. Doctors recommend that those who have been exposed to the measles virus to contact a doctor if they are experiencing symptoms and are not immunized.

In 2019, there were only 20 confirmed cases of measles in [Los Angeles County].

From 2000 to 2018, it has been estimated that 23 million deaths were prevented worldwide due to the vaccination. There is a very low chance of getting infected with measles, as most people are vaccinated at a young age. The Center of Disease Control recommends getting 2 doses of the measles vaccination, which is 97% effective against the virus.

If a person is unsure if they are up to date on their shots, it is suggested to find their vaccination record or record of immunization of measles immunity. If there is no record available, it is recommended to get the measles-mumps-rubella [MMR] vaccination. There are no negative repercussions if you get a 2nd dosage of this vaccine.

New and returning college students, healthcare workers, and international travelers are more susceptible to measles, and it is recommended that they get the vaccine.

For more information, please visit https://www.cdc.gov/measles/index.html.

